5000|$|In 1984, Kotlikoff wrote a {{fundamental}} paper entitled [...] "Deficit Delusion", {{which appeared in}} The Public Interest. This {{was the first of}} a series of papers and books (see, e.g., Generational Accounting and Generational Policy) by Kotlikoff, including work with co-authors, showing, via examples, that in economic models featuring rational agents, [...] "the" [...] deficit is a figment of language, not economics. I.e., the deficit is not economically well defined. Instead, what governments measure as [...] "the" [...] deficit is entirely a result of the language they use to label <b>government</b> <b>receipts</b> and payments.|$|E
